04385nam a22005295i 9780226247045DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20152015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226247045  a(DE-B1597)522657  a(OCoLC)907238074  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQL737.P6bE58 2016 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a599.79152231 aElsner, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDiving Seals and Meditating Yogis :bStrategic Metabolic Retreats /cRobert Elsner. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (192 p.) :b7 halftones, 14 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Strategic metabolic retreats -- t2. Marine mammal divers -- t3. Meditating yogis -- t4. Cardiovascular and metabolic interactions in diving seals -- t5. Regulatory mechanisms in the seal’s dives -- t6. The conditioning phenomenon -- t7. Hibernation and diving -- t8. Human divers -- t9. Resistances to asphyxia -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe comparative physiology of seemingly disparate organisms often serves as a surprising pathway to biological enlightenment. How appropriate, then, that Robert Elsner sheds new light on the remarkable physiology of diving seals through comparison with members of our own species on quests toward enlightenment: meditating yogis. As Elsner reveals, survival in extreme conditions such as those faced by seals is often not about running for cover or coming up for air, but rather about working within the confines of an environment and suppressing normal bodily function. Animals in this withdrawn state display reduced resting metabolic rates and are temporarily less dependent upon customary levels of oxygen. For diving seals—creatures especially well-adapted to prolonged submergence in the ocean’s cold depths—such periods of rest lengthen dive endurance. But while human divers share modest, brief adjustments of suppressed metabolism with diving seals, it is the practiced response achieved during deep meditation that is characterized by metabolic rates well below normal levels, sometimes even approaching those of non-exercising diving seals. And the comparison does not end here: hibernating animals, infants during birth, near-drowning victims, and clams at low tide all also display similarly reduced metabolisms. By investigating these states—and the regulatory functions that help maintain them—across a range of species, Elsner offers suggestive insight into the linked biology of survival and well-being.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDiving. 0aMetabolismxRegulation. 0aSeals (Animals)xBehavior. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aseals, diving, yogi, yoga, meditation, mindfulness, relaxation, enlightenment, survival, metabolism, suppression, oxygen, hibernation, infants, birth, labor, drowning, clams, low tide, regulation, anatomy, science, nonfiction, nature, biology, zoology, marine mammals, ocean animals, asphyxia, divers, the bends, conditioning, endurance, breath hold, respiratory physiology, hypoxia, fetus, medicine, health, heart rate.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022624671040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226247045423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226247045/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles